post_text: KACC first day is Thursday, August 20. Please arrive in the student parking lot between 6:45 - 7:00 am. You may enter door #6 if you would like to get breakfast. You will also need to complete the Self-Certification form prior to loading the bus. On the first day the bus driver will have this form for you to complete. This is to verify you feel healthy and is to be turned into the bus driver before being transported to KACC. You will be given extra copies at school for you to have. Also, 5th hour begins at 10:58 am so you will go immediately to your class once you return if it is your in-person learning day at WCHS.

post_text: Some history about Wanda Kendall, the woman, not the school.
shared_text:
Old Courthouse Museum - Watseka
May 7 at 1:13 PM ¬∑

Pictured here are attendees at a May 29, 1954, party for Wanda Kendall, veteran Iroquois County School teacher, for whom the Wanda Kendall elementary school in Watseka is named. Miss Wanda Kendall, an Iroquois County native, was a teacher for 43 years. She graduated from Watseka High School in 1904 and taught at country schools. She began her career as teacher and principal at Donovan Elementary School in 1916, came to the Watseka schools in 1920, and the St. George School for Girls in Chicago in 1940. After retiring from teaching in 1956, she served as the Nettie Davis School secretary. When the 1966 elementary school was built, it was named in honor of her. Pictured: Amey McKim, Wanda Kendall, Bertha Butzow, Nettie Davis, Mary Sullivan, Mabel Rhoades, May Pratt (partly visible in rear), and Lettie Garfield.

She began her career as teacher and principal at Donovan Elementary School in 1916, came to the Watseka schools in 1920, and the St. George School for Girls in Chicago in 1940. After retiring from teaching in 1956, she served as the Nettie Davis School secretary. When the 1966 elementary school was built, it was named in honor of her. üéâThe 2020 Post Prom Committee raised over $12, 000 by the generosity of local businesses and community members. THANK YOU!üéâ

Due to the uncertainty surrounding COVID 19, we've had to adjust our post prom. We are offering EVERY WCHS junior and senior student the opportunity to select gift cards from local businesses that contributed to post prom this year. Each student will get $90 worth of gift cards along with a gift bag of goodies during our curbside event. There will also be names drawn for additional prizes!

We are disappointed to not take a trip, but excited to give all of our students a monetary gift and give back to our local small businesses. All WCHS juniors and seniors need to fill out the form on their Google Class of page.

See you curbside on July 11th from 10-1pm!

post_text: Some of Mrs. Bruens' First Grade students were able to connect yesterday morning using the platform called ZOOM! Mrs. Bruens and her students did a show and tell while talking with everyone. They got to see toys, siblings, and pets. Her class is hopeful to do weekly ZOOM calls until they can all see each other again at school!
